<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sir William Dunn Sch of Pathology</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/0448F339-E241-4943-9A66-F7F3E6E6A16B"><gtr:id>0448F339-E241-4943-9A66-F7F3E6E6A16B</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Alexandre</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Akoulitchev</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/AF4F847D-E531-44BF-8FB1-2237D9E4CC38"><gtr:id>AF4F847D-E531-44BF-8FB1-2237D9E4CC38</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Nicholas</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Jarvis</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Proudfoot</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=G0200452"><gtr:id>14890BA1-BF32-4D01-9B95-73DB2DD66DA1</gtr:id><gtr:title>Interconnections between splicing, polyadenylation and promoter proximal transcription in eukaryotes</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0200452</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The objectives of this research programme are to unravel a fundamental aspect of how eukaryotic genes work to produce the essential protein building blocks of the cell and organism. We have recently discovered that the basic biochemical mechanism of gene transcription, in which an activated gene is copied into RNA may be further enhanced by a process called splicing. Splicing was hitherto perceived as a separate process to transcription that acts to convert the initial RNA copy of the gene into a functional messenger RNA which is then translated into the gene?s final protein product. However we have now discovered that splicing also directly activates gene transcription. This research programme aims to characterise this new aspect of gene regulation in full molecular detail. The completion of the human genome sequence (and other eukaryotic genomes) has produced a clear divide between our massive knowledge of the basic genetic blueprint in man and how exactly this genetic data is interpreted by the cell into biological function. This research programme aims to unravel a newly discovered but key feature of how genes of eukaryotes (especially man) function.
NJP is a Lecturer and Tutor at Oxford University and as such teaches advanced aspects of Science relating to this research programme to both Biochemistry and Medical students at Oxford University. Both NJP and AA give numerous lectures about their research at conferences and at invited seminars in the UK as well as internationally.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Interconnections between mRNA processing and transcription are well established for the 3? end of eukaryotic genes where cleavage/polyadenylation promotes transcriptional termination. We have now discovered a further remarkable interconnection between promoter proximal splicing and transcriptional activation at the 5? end of eukaryotic genes. This programme aims to characterise in molecular detail this U1snRNA mediated mechanism by which mRNA processing activates transcription in mammals, retroviruses (HIV-1) and yeast. We will firstly apply in vitro transcription and molecular interaction analysis to determine how U1snRNA plays a dual role in both transcription and splicing. The key issue to be investigated is how U1snRNA performs it double function as the RNA component of both U1snRNP and TFIIH. We will further investigate the possibility that in retroviruses, such as HIV-1 the TAR RNA sequence transcribed from the viral 5?LTR acts as a mimic to U1snRNA and so allows this virus to bypass U1snRNA activation of transcription. Chimeric U1/HIV-1 minigene constructs will be created and tested in a coupled in vitro mRNA processing/transcription system. Also the mechanism of 5?LTR poly(A) site suppression will be investigated as this is likely to relate to U1snRNA activation of transcription. To substantiate these in vitro experiments in a more physiological situation we will finally investigate the significance of splicing enhancement of transcription using the simple eukaryote S.cerevisiae. Since only a minority of S. cerevisiae genes possess introns, we will determine if the promoters of this gene class are specifically competent to respond to splicing enhancement. As a backup to in vivo analysis in yeast we will also employ RNAi mediated degradation of specific mRNAs in mammalian cell culture. This will allow us to substantially reduce the expression of specific factors involved in U1snRNA mediated activation of transcription and so test the role of such factors in vivo. The successful outcome of these experiments will have an important impact on current understanding of eukaryotic gene expression.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1046508</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>1853834</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Wellcome Trust Programme Grant (Transcription termination: interconnections between transcription and pre-mRNA processing)</gtr:description><gtr:end>2011-03-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>The Wellcome Trust Ltd</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>BC759735-EE46-440E-A3D0-CFCC43CD8CEE</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2006-04-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>250000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:descripti